1. Adding 3 to every output shifts every point up 3 units. The 
 graph of $g$ is the graph of $f$ shifted **up 3 units**. The 
 vertex moves from $(0, 0)$ to $(0, 3)$.

2. Subtracting 5 from every output shifts every point down 5 units. 
 The graph of $h$ is the graph of $f$ shifted **down 5 units**. 
 The vertex moves from $(0, 0)$ to $(0, -5)$.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.5]
 (-3,0) – (3,0) node[right] {$x$};
 (0,-6) – (0,7) node[above] {$y$};
 plot (, {}) node[right] { $x^2$};
 plot (, { + 3}) node[right] { $x^2+3$};
 plot (, { - 5}) node[right] { $x^2-5$};
 in {-5,-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5,6} (0.1,) – (-0.1,);
tikzpicture
center

1. Replacing $x$ with $x - 4$ shifts right 4 units. The starting 
 point of $f$ (at the origin) moves to $(4, 0)$. The domain changes 
 from $[0, \infty)$ to $[4, \infty)$.

2. Replacing $x$ with $x + 2$ shifts left 2 units. The starting 
 point moves to $(-2, 0)$. The domain changes from $[0, \infty)$ to 
 $[-2, \infty)$.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.6]
 (-3,0) – (7,0) node[right] {$x$};
 (0,-0.5) – (0,3) node[above] {$y$};
 plot (, {sqrt()}) 
 node[right] { $\sqrt{x}$};
 plot (, {sqrt(-4)}) 
 node[right] { $\sqrt{x-4}$};
 plot (, {sqrt(+2)}) 
 node[above] { $\sqrt{x+2}$};
 in {-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5,6} (,0.1) – (,-0.1) node[below] {$\x$};
tikzpicture
center

