content.solution:
1. $g(x) = -\sqrt{x}$ reflects $f$ across the $x$-axis. The graph 
 now extends downward instead of upward.

 Domain: $[0, \infty)$ (unchanged); Range: $(-\infty, 0]$

2. $h(x) = \sqrt{-x}$ reflects $f$ across the $y$-axis. The graph 
 now extends to the left instead of the right.

 Domain: $(-\infty, 0]$; Range: $[0, \infty)$

3. $p(x) = -\sqrt{-x}$ applies both reflections. The graph is in 
 the third quadrant.

 Domain: $(-\infty, 0]$; Range: $(-\infty, 0]$

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.55]
 (-4,0) – (4,0) node[right] {$x$};
 (0,-3) – (0,3) node[above] {$y$};

 % Original
 plot (, {sqrt()});
 at (3.2, 2.1) { $\sqrt{x}$};

 % Reflect across x-axis
 plot (, {-sqrt()});
 at (3.2, -2.1) { $-\sqrt{x}$};

 % Reflect across y-axis
 plot (, {sqrt(-)});
 at (-3.2, 2.1) { $\sqrt{-x}$};

 % Both reflections
 plot (, {-sqrt(-)});
 at (-3.2, -2.1) { $-\sqrt{-x}$};
tikzpicture
center

- $g(x) = 3x^2$ multiplies all outputs by 3. The parabola is 
 "narrower" (vertically stretched). At $x = 1$: $f(1) = 1$, $g(1) = 3$.

- $h(x) = \frac{1}{2}x^2$ multiplies all outputs by $\frac{1}{2}$. 
 The parabola is "wider" (vertically compressed). At $x = 2$: 
 $f(2) = 4$, $h(2) = 2$.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.5]
 (-3,0) – (3,0) node[right] {$x$};
 (0,-0.5) – (0,6) node[above] {$y$};
 plot (, {});
 plot (, {3*}) node[right] { $3x^2$};
 plot (, {0.5*}) node[right] { $\frac{1}{2}x^2$};
 at (2.3, 3.5) { $x^2$};
tikzpicture
center
